00:59.000 --> 01:01.167
Reporter: WHAT HAPPENED
TO THE FISHING VESSEL

01:01.200 --> 01:03.233
AND ITS CREW OF SIX
OFF THE COAST OF ALASKA

01:03.267 --> 01:05.333
REMAINS A MYSTERY.

01:20.600 --> 01:23.567
-- Captions by VITAC --
www.vitac.com

01:23.600 --> 01:26.567
CAPTIONS PAID FOR BY
DISCOVERY COMMUNICATIONS

01:26.600 --> 01:29.767
[ WIND HOWLING ]

01:35.100 --> 01:37.933
Narrator: NEARING THE END
OF THE WINTER SEASON...

01:37.967 --> 01:41.100
OH, NO!

01:41.133 --> 01:43.267
THAT'S NOT GOOD.

01:43.300 --> 01:45.200
IT'S A PIECE
OF [BLEEP] POT.

01:45.233 --> 01:47.500
Narrator: ...THE FLEET
CONTINUES TO STRUGGLE

01:47.533 --> 01:48.733
TO FILL THEIR QUOTAS.

01:48.767 --> 01:51.200
Sig: A LOT OF THIS BIOMASS
HAS BEEN PICKED THROUGH.

01:51.233 --> 01:53.267
A LOT OF THIS CRAB
HAS BEEN HAMMERED ON,

01:53.300 --> 01:54.733
YOU KNOW,
ALL THROUGH THE SEASON.

01:54.767 --> 01:56.433
WHOA.

01:56.467 --> 02:00.167
Narrator: IT'S A PERPETUAL GRIND
TO FILL THE TANKS.

02:00.200 --> 02:04.200
Jake: THE WHOLE FLEET
IS FISHING ON 25s, 50s, 100s,

02:04.233 --> 02:06.567
AND THEY'RE ALL SAYING
THE SAME THING.

02:06.600 --> 02:09.233
WE ARE NEVER GOING HOME.

02:09.267 --> 02:10.967
Narrator:
AND NOTHING IS SAFE

02:11.067 --> 02:13.067
UNTIL THE BOAT'S TIED UP
AT DOCK...

02:13.067 --> 02:15.967
I DON'T WANT TO WASTE ANY TIME.
TIME IS MONEY.

02:16.067 --> 02:18.333
Narrator: ...AND OUT OF REACH
OF THE BERING SEA.

02:18.367 --> 02:21.967
I'M SETTING THE BAR HIGH.
I'M KNOCKING ON WOOD RIGHT NOW.

02:22.067 --> 02:25.167
[ WIND HOWLING ]

02:30.833 --> 02:33.067
Narrator: ON THE WIZARD...

02:33.067 --> 02:36.233
Keith:
WE GOT OUR CRAB ON BOARD.

02:36.267 --> 02:40.367
300 MILES, WE GOT
48 HOURS OF RUN TIME.

02:42.800 --> 02:46.067
Narrator: HIS TANKS FULL,
CAPTAIN KEITH COLBURN

02:46.067 --> 02:47.967
HEADS IN TO END HIS SEASON.

02:52.133 --> 02:53.433
AND THE WEATHER SUCKS.

02:53.467 --> 02:54.833
THE WEATHER'S NOT
GETTING ANY BETTER.

02:54.867 --> 02:59.667
IT'S STILL BLOWING HARD OUT
OF THE SOUTHEAST, 35 TO 45.

02:59.700 --> 03:00.933
Narrator: BUT IN HIS WAY,

03:00.967 --> 03:05.967
300 MILES OF ARCTIC WINDS
AND 25-FOOT SEAS.

03:06.067 --> 03:07.633
Monte: WE'RE HEADING TO TOWN.
WE GOT ALL THE GEAR ON THE BOAT.

03:07.667 --> 03:09.433
EVERYBODY'S PRETTY HAPPY,
BUT THE BAD NEWS IS,

03:09.467 --> 03:12.533
WE'RE IN FOR YET
ANOTHER STORM OUT HERE.

03:12.567 --> 03:14.667
[ BOAT CREAKING ]

03:14.700 --> 03:24.067
*

03:24.100 --> 03:26.100
[ ALARM BLARING ]

03:29.100 --> 03:31.533
Keith: WOW.
THIS IS NOT GOOD.

03:33.133 --> 03:37.300
MOUSE, WE'VE GOT ABOUT
A THREE-DEGREE LIFT RIGHT NOW.

03:37.333 --> 03:39.933
I MEAN, WE ARE DEFINITELY
LISTING HARD TO STARBOARD.

03:48.067 --> 03:50.067
Narrator: THE ALARM INDICATES
THAT THE WIZARD

03:50.067 --> 03:52.333
HAS BEGUN ROLLING
DANGEROUSLY TO ONE SIDE.

03:52.367 --> 03:55.267
WHOA!

03:55.300 --> 03:57.633
[ BOAT CREAKING ]

03:57.667 --> 04:04.667
*

04:04.700 --> 04:06.200
THIS HAS GOT ME NERVOUS
RIGHT NOW.

04:06.233 --> 04:08.067
COULD BECOME PRETTY SERIOUS
PRETTY QUICK

04:08.067 --> 04:09.967
IF WE DON'T ADDRESS IT.

04:10.067 --> 04:13.067
Monte: ALL RIGHT, LET'S HEAD
BACK THIS WAY.

04:13.067 --> 04:15.700
Narrator: ON DECK,
VETERAN MONTE COLBURN SEARCHES

04:15.733 --> 04:17.833
FOR THE CAUSE OF THE IMBALANCE.

04:22.533 --> 04:24.967
Keith: WE'RE LOOKING AT ABOUT
A SIX-DEGREE STARBOARD LIST,

04:25.067 --> 04:26.867
WHICH IS WAY MORE
THAN I WANT TO HAVE.

04:30.200 --> 04:33.767
Monte: I DON'T SEE ANYTHING.

04:33.800 --> 04:36.500
YOU KNOW, WE'VE GOT
SOLID 15-FOOTERS,

04:36.533 --> 04:40.833
AND THERE'S THE OCCASIONAL
25-FOOT WAVE COMING THROUGH.

04:40.867 --> 04:43.133
RIGHT NOW, WE CAN'T AFFORD
ANY WEIGHT ON THE BOAT

04:43.167 --> 04:44.400
BECAUSE THE WEIGHT
WILL ALL SHIFT

04:44.433 --> 04:45.867
TO THE LOWEST PART OF THE BOAT,

04:45.900 --> 04:47.200
WHICH IS THE STARBOARD SIDE,

04:47.233 --> 04:50.267
AND ADD EVEN MORE
WEIGHT OVER THERE.

04:50.300 --> 04:51.933
AND THESE ARE THE KIND
OF PROBLEMS

04:51.967 --> 04:53.433
THAT ARE THE FINAL STRAW

04:53.467 --> 04:57.467
THAT'S CAUSED BOATS
TO GO DOWN.

04:57.500 --> 05:00.067
Monte: SEE THAT?

05:00.067 --> 05:02.900
THIS IS IT HERE.

05:02.933 --> 05:05.700
SO YOU SEE THIS BOOT'S
GOT A BIG SPLIT IN IT.

05:05.733 --> 05:07.933
[ PHONE RINGS ]

05:07.967 --> 05:09.833
HELLO?

05:15.233 --> 05:16.600
ALL RIGHT, OKAY.

05:16.633 --> 05:18.933
Monte: BLOWING WATER UP
INSIDE OF THERE.

05:21.100 --> 05:23.600
Narrator: MONTE HAS LOCATED
A RIP IN THE COVER

05:23.633 --> 05:26.200
OF THE STARBOARD FUEL TANK VENT.

05:26.233 --> 05:29.900
WITH OCEAN WATER POURING IN,
THE EXTRA WEIGHT IN THE TANKS

05:29.933 --> 05:32.667
IS MAKING THE WIZARD LIST.

05:32.700 --> 05:36.067
LEFT UNCHECKED, IT COULD
CAUSE THE BOAT TO CAPSIZE.

05:36.067 --> 05:41.133
*

05:41.167 --> 05:42.633
THE BOAT
IS STARTING TO TIP MORE AND MORE

05:42.667 --> 05:45.233
AND MORE TO STARBOARD.

05:45.267 --> 05:48.233
[ BOAT CREAKING ]

05:48.267 --> 05:51.167
Monte:
THIS WAS ATTACHED TO THE VENT.

05:51.200 --> 05:53.467
WELL, IT'S GOT
A HOLE IN IT HERE.

05:53.500 --> 05:55.733
IT'S SPLIT, SO IT REALLY
WASN'T DOING MUCH

05:55.767 --> 05:59.067
FROM STOPPING THE WATER
FROM TRYING TO ENTER THE VENT.

06:02.733 --> 06:04.867
Keith: MONTE AND THE CHIEF
ARE UP FORWARD RIGHT NOW,

06:04.900 --> 06:06.933
TRYING TO FIND
SOME KIND OF TUBE

06:06.967 --> 06:09.867
OR ANYTHING THEY CAN TO TRY
AND SECURE THAT VENT.

06:14.367 --> 06:15.600
Narrator: MONTE'S FIX?

06:15.633 --> 06:18.067
TAKE AN OLD NEOPRENE
SURVIVAL SUIT

06:18.067 --> 06:22.267
AND RESHAPE IT TO FIT
OVER THE FUEL TANK VENT,

06:22.300 --> 06:23.900
KEEPING WATER
FROM FLOODING IN.

06:23.933 --> 06:27.300
WE GOT THE GUYS -- YOU CAN SEE
THE GUYS UP FORWARD WORKING.

06:27.333 --> 06:29.533
THAT'S KIND OF
INGENIOUS, ACTUALLY.

06:32.800 --> 06:34.433
OKAY, SO NOW WE'VE CUT
THE FINGERS OFF,

06:34.467 --> 06:38.767
AND YOU CAN SEE THAT
THIS WILL VENT THE FUEL TANK.

06:38.800 --> 06:40.833
[ BOAT CREAKING ]

06:49.933 --> 06:51.833
IT'S A REALLY GOOD USE
OF AN OLD SURVIVAL SUIT,

06:51.867 --> 06:53.867
I'LL TELL YOU THAT RIGHT NOW.

06:53.900 --> 06:56.900
WE GOT TO HOPE IT'S JUST THAT.

06:56.933 --> 06:58.300
AND THAT SOMETHING ELSE --

06:58.333 --> 07:00.700
THAT'S SOMETHING WE CAN'T
REALLY WORK ON OUR HERE.

07:05.267 --> 07:08.167
Narrator:
PUTTING HIS FAITH IN HIS
BROTHER'S MAKESHIFT PATCH,

07:08.200 --> 07:11.867
KEITH POINTS THE WIZARD
TOWARD DUTCH HARBOR.

07:11.900 --> 07:13.667
Keith: BECAUSE LISTS TURN
INTO BAD LISTS,

07:13.700 --> 07:20.800
AND BAD LISTS TURN INTO...
MAYDAYS AND MISSING VESSELS.

07:20.833 --> 07:23.267
I JUST HAD A SNEAKING SUSPICION
THAT THE BERING SEA

07:23.300 --> 07:25.600
WAS NOT GONNA LET US
LEAVE PLEASANTLY.

07:25.633 --> 07:31.367
*

07:31.400 --> 07:34.433
Narrator:
60 MILES NORTHWEST...

07:35.900 --> 07:37.800
...ON THE 107-FOOT SAGA...

07:37.833 --> 07:39.933
Jake:
WE'LL PICK UP THE TOWN SOAK.

07:39.967 --> 07:43.933
I CALL IT THE BLIND MAN'S DREAM
'CAUSE I SET IT BLIND.

07:43.967 --> 07:47.333
JUST TRYING TO HUNT
AND CATCH 'EM.

07:47.367 --> 07:48.867
Narrator:
...CAPTAIN JAKE ANDERSON

07:48.900 --> 07:52.667
APPROACHES POTS THAT HE SET
BEFORE HE WAS FORCED INTO TOWN.

07:52.700 --> 07:57.600
THIS STRING WAS SET 12 DAYS AGO
WHEN LUCE FELL OFF THE STACK.

07:59.800 --> 08:01.933
-LUCE!
-WHAT HAPPENED? WHAT HAPPENED!

08:01.967 --> 08:03.733
-LUCE!
-LUCE!

08:03.767 --> 08:05.633
Narrator:
NEW TO WORKING THE STACK...

08:05.667 --> 08:08.867
-HE'S DOWN!
-MAN DOWN, JAKE!

08:08.900 --> 08:11.333
Narrator:
...CREWMAN LUCE BATELLA

08:11.367 --> 08:12.600
FELL TO THE DECK...

08:12.633 --> 08:15.333
I'LL JUST FOLLOW YOU,
ALL RIGHT?

08:15.367 --> 08:17.700
...AND SUFFERED A SERIOUS
HEAD INJURY.

08:17.733 --> 08:20.233
Jake: I'M GOING IN.

08:20.267 --> 08:21.467
12 DAYS AGO.

08:21.500 --> 08:25.367
YOU KNOW WHAT I COULD
HAVE DONE WITH 12 DAYS?

08:25.400 --> 08:29.367
I -- I NEED 10,000 POUNDS
A DAY, MINIMUM.

08:34.067 --> 08:36.667
I HAVE TO BE INTO THE PLANT
FOR MY OFFLOAD DATE,

08:36.700 --> 08:41.533
SO I'VE ONLY GOT
TWO DAYS TO FISH.

08:41.567 --> 08:45.800
THIS STUFF'S BEEN SOAKING
FOR A LONG TIME NOW.

08:45.833 --> 08:48.133
HOPEFULLY IT PAYS OFF GOOD.

08:48.167 --> 08:51.567
Narrator: WHILE IN TOWN, JAKE
MANAGED TO RESTOCK HIS DECK.

08:51.600 --> 08:55.567
WE HAVE TWO NEW CREW MEMBERS,
CANDITO AND KYLE.

08:55.600 --> 08:57.167
NOW THAT I GOT FIVE GUYS,

08:57.200 --> 09:01.133
I SHOULD BE ABLE TO JUST JAM
THESE POTS DOWN THEIR THROATS.

09:01.167 --> 09:05.800
SO THE FIRST ROUND, I'M HOPING
THAT I CAN GET THREE FULL TANKS,

09:05.833 --> 09:10.067
AND IT'S ALL GONNA DEPEND
ON THIS STRING RIGHT HERE.

09:10.067 --> 09:12.233
THERE WE GO, FIRST POT.

09:12.267 --> 09:18.533
*

09:18.567 --> 09:24.833
*

09:24.867 --> 09:27.433
I HOPE IT BRINGS LOTS
AND LOTS OF CRABBIES.

09:31.333 --> 09:34.867
Man: COME ON, BABY!

09:34.900 --> 09:36.133
Jake: COME ON, BABY!

09:38.400 --> 09:41.167
-COMING UP.
-WHOO!

09:41.200 --> 09:46.267
*

09:46.300 --> 09:48.767
Jake: OH, NO.

09:48.800 --> 09:54.500
*

09:54.533 --> 09:56.333
THAT SUCKS.

09:58.700 --> 10:01.267
THIS IS ROUGH.

10:05.833 --> 10:07.367
OOH.

10:07.400 --> 10:08.600
THIS ISN'T GETTING US ANYWHERE.

10:13.033 --> 10:15.200
[ GRUNTS ]

10:15.233 --> 10:18.667
[BLEEP] GOD, THESE SUCK!

10:20.633 --> 10:23.900
-WHY?
-OH.

10:23.933 --> 10:26.567
FISHING DEFINITELY SUCKS.

10:30.067 --> 10:32.467
THERE'S NOTHING I CAN DO
EXCEPT FOR KEEP HAULING

10:32.500 --> 10:34.533
AND KEEP CRAB COMING ON BOARD.

10:34.567 --> 10:36.333
Narrator:
DESPITE LOW NUMBERS...

10:36.367 --> 10:41.167
KEEP RESETTING, PICK,
RESET, PICK, RESET.

10:41.200 --> 10:43.900
Narrator: ...JAKE HAS NO CHOICE
BUT TO GRIND IT OUT.

10:43.933 --> 10:45.400
THAT AIN'T GONNA DO IT.

10:45.433 --> 10:47.833
THAT SUCKS, MAN!

10:50.100 --> 10:52.600
WE MIGHT START HAVING
TO PACK LEAD IN THE CRAB

10:52.633 --> 10:55.100
JUST TO GET OUR QUOTA.

10:57.733 --> 10:59.167
[ RADIO BEEPS ]

11:01.467 --> 11:04.433
YEAH, ROGER.

11:10.200 --> 11:11.333
NOTHING HERE.

11:11.367 --> 11:13.333
[BLEEP]

11:13.367 --> 11:16.867
Sig: WOW.

11:16.900 --> 11:19.300
Narrator:
CAPTAIN SIG HANSEN CHECKS UP

11:19.333 --> 11:20.733
ON HIS FORMER DECKHAND.

11:20.767 --> 11:22.467
I HAD HIGH HOPES
FOR THIS STRING.

11:22.500 --> 11:26.500
I HAD TWO PROSPECT STRINGS
AND JUST CHECKED ON FRESH SET,

11:26.533 --> 11:28.733
FRESH SOAK.

11:28.767 --> 11:31.400
OH, NO.

11:31.433 --> 11:32.433
NOTHING.

11:32.467 --> 11:35.333
50s, YOU KNOW,
THE WHOLE WAY.

11:35.367 --> 11:38.733
SO, I THINK THEY MIGHT BE
GOING OFF THE BITE.

11:38.767 --> 11:40.867
[ SIGHS ]

11:40.900 --> 11:44.067
-WHY?!
-AWW.

11:44.067 --> 11:47.967
Narrator: LIKE JAKE, SIG HAS
BEEN PLAGUED WITH LOW NUMBERS.

11:48.067 --> 11:50.467
MAYBE YOU CAN SEND ME
A BIRTHDAY CARD NEXT SEPTEMBER

11:50.500 --> 11:52.933
WHEN I'M STILL GETTING
MY LAST TRIP IN.

11:52.967 --> 11:57.067
[ LAUGHS ]

11:57.067 --> 11:59.200
IT'LL TURN AROUND.

11:59.233 --> 12:03.200
YEAH, I KNOW.
I GOT TODAY AND TOMORROW.

12:03.233 --> 12:04.400
ROGER, YEAH.

12:04.433 --> 12:06.667
WELL, BE REAL CAREFUL.

12:06.700 --> 12:09.267
EVERYBODY SAFE,
NO CRAZY STUFF,

12:09.300 --> 12:11.367
EVERYBODY GOES HOME,
FINGERS AND TOES,

12:11.400 --> 12:12.500
ALL THAT GOOD STUFF.

12:12.533 --> 12:15.667
-ALL RIGHT.
-I'M OUT.

12:18.367 --> 12:20.767
[ BLOWS RASPBERRY ]

12:20.800 --> 12:28.733
*

12:28.767 --> 12:36.700
*

12:36.733 --> 12:39.200
[ BIRDS CAWING ]

12:51.633 --> 12:54.067
Narrator:
ACROSS THE BERING SEA,

12:54.100 --> 12:56.300
THE UNITED STATES
COAST GUARD BROADCASTS

12:56.333 --> 12:58.600
AN URGENT MESSAGE
TO THE FLEET.

13:18.867 --> 13:20.767
[ HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING ]

13:20.800 --> 13:23.533
Officer: WE GOT ABOUT 4 1/2
HOURS OF FUEL ONBOARD.

13:23.567 --> 13:26.633
IT'LL TAKE US JUST SHY
OF TWO HOURS TO GET THERE.

13:26.667 --> 13:29.900
Officer #2: ROGER.

13:29.933 --> 13:32.433
Narrator: AN MH-60
JAYHAWK HELICOPTER

13:32.467 --> 13:34.300
IS DISPATCHED TO THE LOCATION

13:34.333 --> 13:37.533
OF THE EMERGENCY SIGNAL'S
LAST-KNOWN COORDINATES.

14:01.633 --> 14:03.733
[ WIND HOWLING ]

14:11.133 --> 14:15.733
Officer: THE LAST CIAS IS
CURRENTLY 3-1-0 FOR TWO MILES.

14:15.767 --> 14:18.500
IT WAS DRIFTING
IN THAT DIRECTION.

14:24.067 --> 14:27.467
Narrator:
JUST OFF ST. GEORGE ISLAND...

14:27.500 --> 14:30.067
Officer #2: ACTIVE 6-0-3-7,
JUST WANT YOU TO BE ADVISED,

14:30.100 --> 14:33.500
WE ARE COMMENCING OUR SEARCH
PATTERN AT THIS TIME.

14:33.533 --> 14:35.233
...THE COAST GUARD
HELICOPTER SEARCHES

14:35.267 --> 14:38.600
FOR THE LOCATION OF A SIGNAL
FROM AN EMERGENCY BEACON

14:38.633 --> 14:41.633
ASSIGNED TO THE FISHING
VESSEL DESTINATION.

15:46.933 --> 15:49.567
THE LIFE RING
IS AN IMPORTANT FIND.

15:49.600 --> 15:51.800
IF IT BELONGS
TO THE DESTINATION,

15:51.833 --> 15:53.967
IT WILL CONFIRM
THE IDENTITY OF THE BOAT.

16:00.800 --> 16:04.567
THE COAST GUARD REACHES OUT TO
A NEARBY GOOD SAMARITAN CRABBER,

16:04.600 --> 16:08.433
FISHING VESSEL SILVER SPRAY,
TO RETRIEVE THE LIFE RING.

16:24.067 --> 16:25.333
YEAH, ROGER.

16:30.900 --> 16:41.133
*

16:41.167 --> 16:54.100
*

16:54.133 --> 16:55.933
OH, MAN.

17:28.567 --> 17:29.900
Narrator: THE DEBRIS FIELD

17:29.933 --> 17:32.967
INDICATES THE BOAT SUFFERED
A CATASTROPHIC EVENT...

17:37.767 --> 17:41.067
...INTENSIFYING THE SEARCH
FOR THE MISSING CREW.

18:06.233 --> 18:09.933
[ WIND HOWLING ]

18:09.967 --> 18:12.867
135 MILES NORTHWEST...

18:16.300 --> 18:18.500
...ON THE NORTHWESTERN...

18:18.533 --> 18:20.367
[ RADIO BEEPS ]

18:29.833 --> 18:32.667
NO.
I -- YOU KNOW WHAT?

18:32.700 --> 18:36.233
I HEARD SOMETHING,
SOMEBODY TALKING ON 18,

18:36.267 --> 18:39.133
AND THEN...

18:39.167 --> 18:41.800
I COULDN'T PICK IT UP.

18:41.833 --> 18:43.900
ARE YOU TALKING ABOUT
JEFF'S DESTINATION?

18:43.933 --> 18:46.933
MY -- MY BUDDY?

18:46.967 --> 18:49.533
WHAT?
-YEAH, ROGER.

19:19.800 --> 19:22.067
[ RADIO BEEPING ]

19:34.867 --> 19:37.067
IS --

19:37.067 --> 19:38.700
DID THEY GET OFF A MAYDAY?

19:43.233 --> 19:46.100
[ RADIO BEEPS ]

19:47.333 --> 19:49.967
[ SIGHS ]

19:50.067 --> 19:56.233
*

19:56.267 --> 19:57.633
OKAY, CASEY.

19:57.667 --> 20:03.700
NO, THANKS FOR DOING THAT,
SO...THANKS FOR LETTING ME KNOW.

20:03.733 --> 20:04.733
THANK YOU.

20:04.767 --> 20:12.900
*

20:27.800 --> 20:30.700
I KNOW YOU WANT ME TO PROBABLY
SAY SOMETHING, BUT --

20:34.433 --> 20:35.767
MAYBE JUST GIVE ME A LITTLE BIT,

20:35.800 --> 20:41.600
AND, UH, I'LL TELL YOU
WHAT I THINK, OKAY?

20:41.633 --> 20:43.600
Producer:
ABSOLUTELY, SIR.

20:43.633 --> 20:48.733
*

20:48.767 --> 20:51.467
[ LIGHTER CLICKS ]

20:59.900 --> 21:02.833
[ GULLS CAWING ]

21:02.867 --> 21:04.333
Narrator:
ON THE NORTHWESTERN...

21:04.367 --> 21:10.067
*

21:10.100 --> 21:14.367
[ GULL CAWING ]

21:14.400 --> 21:17.833
YEAH, THIS --

21:17.867 --> 21:19.867
THAT'S [BLEEP] UP.

21:19.900 --> 21:21.833
Narrator: ...CAPTAIN SIG
HAS RECEIVED NEWS

21:21.867 --> 21:25.500
THAT THE FISHING VESSEL
DESTINATION HAS SUNK,

21:25.533 --> 21:28.367
AND ITS CREW HAS GONE MISSING.

21:28.400 --> 21:31.967
Sig: I DON'T KNOW IF I SHOULD
TELL MY GUYS, I DON'T KNOW.

21:32.067 --> 21:34.533
THEY'RE ALL FRIENDS.

21:39.233 --> 21:41.733
WE'RE ALL FRIENDS.

21:45.200 --> 21:47.167
GET IT OUT OF THE WAY.

21:47.200 --> 21:50.767
[BLEEP]

21:55.067 --> 21:57.800
[ SIGHS ]

21:57.833 --> 21:59.367
NICK!
-YEAH?

21:59.400 --> 22:01.233
-BAD NEWS.
-OH.

22:01.267 --> 22:02.567
REAL BAD.

22:02.600 --> 22:04.733
Nick: HE'S RIGHT THERE.

22:08.233 --> 22:09.833
DESTINATION.

22:12.700 --> 22:16.700
THEY HAVEN'T HEARD ANYTHING --
7:00 THIS MORNING, 8:00.

22:16.733 --> 22:17.867
NO.

22:17.900 --> 22:20.433
YEAH.

22:22.533 --> 22:26.100
AND THEN THE COAST GUARD,
THEY FOUND --

22:26.133 --> 22:27.667
I THINK THEY FOUND A LIFE RING,

22:27.700 --> 22:33.800
AND I THINK THEY FOUND
SOME DEBRIS, AND THAT'S IT.

22:33.833 --> 22:36.433
LARRY WAS ON THERE.

22:36.467 --> 22:38.267
[BLEEP]
GLENNY'S PROBABLY ON THERE.

22:38.300 --> 22:40.933
MOSTLY LIKELY RAY-RAY
FROM AKUTAN.

22:46.400 --> 22:48.800
JEFF'S ONE OF MY BEST --
BEST FRIENDS.

22:50.767 --> 22:52.933
WE WERE FISHING
TOGETHER FOR YEAS.

22:56.333 --> 22:57.400
THEY GOT PLANES IN THE AIR.

22:57.433 --> 23:00.833
I HEARD A C-130 UP THERE.

23:00.867 --> 23:03.933
SO, SAY A LITTLE PRAYER
FOR DESTINATION.

23:03.967 --> 23:12.100
*

23:12.133 --> 23:13.233
LET'S GET GOING HERE.

23:13.267 --> 23:14.967
WE GOTTA SET THIS STRING HERE.

23:15.067 --> 23:20.233
*

23:20.267 --> 23:22.867
Man: SOMETHING REALLY
WAS WRONG TO HAPPEN.

23:25.067 --> 23:27.067
SOMETHING SERIOUSLY WRONG.

23:32.433 --> 23:34.467
WE'VE NOT GIVEN UP HOPE YET.

23:34.500 --> 23:37.067
DOESN'T SOUND GOOD.

23:42.100 --> 23:43.867
ALL THE GUYS THAT ARE ON
THE BOAT HAVE BEEN ON THE BOAT

23:43.900 --> 23:46.800
FOR A LONG TIME, SO...

23:46.833 --> 23:49.800
AND A FEW OF 'EM WERE REALLY
GOOD FRIENDS OF MINE, AS WELL.

23:49.833 --> 23:53.800
GOT LARRY O. ON THERE
AND GLEN JONES,

23:53.833 --> 23:56.833
JEFF HATHAWAY WAS THE CAPTAIN.

23:56.867 --> 23:59.767
THAT GUY'S BEEN
AROUND A LONG TIME.

23:59.800 --> 24:01.200
THERE'S STILL A CHANCE
THEY MAY BE OUT THERE.

24:01.233 --> 24:03.067
THERE'S STILL A CHANCE
THEY COULD BE IN A LIFE RAFT

24:03.100 --> 24:04.433
FOR ALL WE KNOW.

24:04.467 --> 24:11.467
*

24:11.500 --> 24:13.700
Narrator:
13 MILES SOUTHEAST...

24:13.733 --> 24:17.233
[ RADIO BUZZES ]

24:19.200 --> 24:21.433
Jake: YEAH, ROGER.

24:21.467 --> 24:22.867
Narrator:
...ON THE SAGA...

24:39.733 --> 24:41.900
I DON'T EVEN BELIEVE IT.

24:41.933 --> 24:46.100
I DON'T --
I DON'T KNOW WHAT TO SAY.

24:54.167 --> 24:57.733
ROGER, SORRY, SIG.

24:57.767 --> 25:00.333
I KNOW.

25:00.367 --> 25:03.567
THAT'S HIS GOOD FRIEND.

25:03.600 --> 25:08.200
THE CAPTAIN IS JEFF HATHAWAY,
AND HE'S A REALLY GOOD CAPTAIN.

25:10.833 --> 25:12.200
HEY, GUYS, CAN YOU...

25:15.133 --> 25:18.733
SO CANDITO, I THINK, HAS WORKED
ON THE DESTINATION.

25:18.767 --> 25:21.900
HE'S WORKED FOR JEFF,
AND HE KNOWS PEOPLE OVER THERE.

25:24.600 --> 25:27.500
DO YOU GUYS ALL KNOW
PEOPLE AT THE DESTINATION?

25:32.800 --> 25:36.733
EPIRB WENT OFF, AND THEN
THEY CAN'T FIND 'EM.

25:36.767 --> 25:43.967
ALL THEY FOUND WAS TONNAGE,
LIFE RING, AND...

25:46.833 --> 25:50.067
THERE'S RUMORS THAT THEY WERE
ICING UP OR SOMETHING.

25:50.067 --> 25:52.100
THEY HAD A FULL HAY STACK, TOO.

25:56.700 --> 25:58.967
YEAH, YEAH, YEAH,
THEY'RE STILL LOOKING.

26:01.933 --> 26:04.467
SOMEBODY.

26:09.933 --> 26:12.200
Reporter: WHAT HAPPENED TO THE
FISHING VESSEL DESTINATION

26:12.233 --> 26:14.400
AND ITS CREW OF SIX
OFF THE COAST OF ALASKA

26:14.433 --> 26:17.767
REMAINS A MYSTERY.

26:17.800 --> 26:20.433
Reporter #2: THE COAST GUARD
HAS BEEN SEARCHING

26:20.467 --> 26:23.400
OFF ST. GEORGE ISLAND
ON THE SOUTHERN COAST OF ALASKA.

26:23.433 --> 26:25.167
THE DESTINATION HAD A LIFE RAFT

26:25.200 --> 26:28.300
THAT SHOULD HAVE
AUTOMATICALLY DEPLOYED.

26:28.333 --> 26:30.700
FISHERMEN
AND FAMILIES OF THE LOST

26:30.733 --> 26:33.933
ARE HOPING FOR THE VERY BEST.

26:33.967 --> 26:35.867
Officer: 6-0-0-5.
6-0-0-5.

26:35.900 --> 26:38.467
SECTOR ANCHORAGE.
SECTOR ANCHORAGE ON.

26:38.500 --> 26:42.067
Narrator: AFTER HOURS OF
SEARCHING FOR THE DESTINATION...

26:42.067 --> 26:43.667
Officer #2:
WE'LL SEARCH THERE.

26:43.700 --> 26:46.067
...THE COAST GUARD HAS
DISPATCHED HELICOPTERS...

26:46.100 --> 26:49.067
Pilot: C-130'S ON SCENE.

26:49.067 --> 26:51.767
...FIXED-WING AIRCRAFT,

26:51.800 --> 26:56.067
AND EVEN THE 378-FOOT
COAST GUARD CUTTER MORGENTHAU

26:56.067 --> 27:00.233
IN A COORDINATED EFFORT TO FIND
THE MISSING CREW AND BOAT.

27:21.100 --> 27:22.833
LOVE IT.

27:24.933 --> 27:27.300
THE SEARCH TEAMS PICKS UP
THE DISTRESS SIGNAL

27:27.333 --> 27:29.333
FROM THE DESTINATION'S EPIRB,

27:29.367 --> 27:31.700
OR EMERGENCY
POSITIONING BEACON...

27:36.600 --> 27:39.400
...GIVING THE COAST GUARD
NEW HOPE.

28:00.167 --> 28:01.567
Narrator:
AFTER HOURS OF SEARCHING...

28:08.400 --> 28:09.633
LOVE IT.

28:09.667 --> 28:12.100
...THE COAST GUARD ZEROES IN
ON A DISTRESS SIGNAL

28:12.133 --> 28:15.300
FROM THE DESTINATION'S
EMERGENCY POSITIONING BEACON.

28:26.267 --> 28:29.500
THE HOPE IS THAT THE BEACON
WILL LEAD THEM TO THE CREW.

28:33.267 --> 28:43.167
*

28:43.200 --> 28:47.733
*

29:09.067 --> 29:10.867
[ EPIRB BEEPING ]

29:33.100 --> 29:41.767
*

29:41.800 --> 29:44.933
*

30:04.833 --> 30:06.900
Narrator:
WITH NO RAFT IN SIGHT,

30:06.933 --> 30:09.400
THE ODDS OF FINDING SURVIVORS
ARE BLEAK.

30:09.433 --> 30:20.267
*

30:20.300 --> 30:21.500
DOWN BELOW...

30:24.567 --> 30:28.000
THE CREW OF THE GOOD SAMARITAN
FISHING VESSEL SILVER SPRAY

30:28.033 --> 30:32.367
SIFTS THROUGH DEBRIS
TO RECOVER THE EMERGENCY BEACON.

30:32.400 --> 30:34.933
OVER THERE!

30:47.667 --> 30:49.733
IT WAS RIGGED!
SOMEBODY TAPED IT!

31:10.700 --> 31:12.800
Narrator:
IDENTIFYING THE BEACON

31:12.833 --> 31:15.367
CONFIRMS THE COAST GUARD'S
WORST FEARS.

31:31.233 --> 31:33.700
YEAH.

31:46.067 --> 31:47.700
[ SNIFFLES ]

31:52.367 --> 31:54.067
I NEED A BREAK.

31:54.067 --> 32:07.633
*

32:13.900 --> 32:16.133
Jake:
THAT'S NOT GOOD AT ALL.

32:16.167 --> 32:17.667
THEY'RE GONE.

32:17.700 --> 32:19.067
CAN'T EVEN FIND 'EM.

32:19.067 --> 32:20.833
NO LIFE RAFT OR NOTHING.

32:25.300 --> 32:27.700
LAST POT RIGHT HERE.

32:29.733 --> 32:32.133
I'M SO GLAD I'M GETTING
OUT OF HERE.

33:06.733 --> 33:09.267
Sig: THEY'RE GONE.

33:14.067 --> 33:16.467
THEY'RE GONE.

33:23.467 --> 33:25.067
[ BEEPING ]

33:34.567 --> 33:38.433
JUST HAD A KID,
JUST GOT MARRIED.

33:38.467 --> 33:41.600
[BLEEP] SEVEN YEARS CLEAN.

33:43.600 --> 33:45.500
[BLEEP] UP.

33:53.900 --> 33:55.333
THIS IS --
[BLEEP] LIKE THIS

33:55.367 --> 33:57.533
IS WHY I DON'T LIKE
COMING OUT HERE ANYMORE.

34:06.700 --> 34:10.100
I DON'T KNOW.
I DON'T KNOW.

34:10.132 --> 34:13.400
HE WAS COMING --
NO, THEY'RE NOT.

34:13.433 --> 34:14.699
THEY CAN'T FIND ANYBODY.

34:14.733 --> 34:17.367
THEY HAD -- THE EPIRB --

34:19.967 --> 34:22.266
June: OH, GOD.

34:31.067 --> 34:33.567
YEAH, I'M THINKING ABOUT IT.

34:40.233 --> 34:43.067
Jake: WHEN YOU HEARD
A BOAT'S GOING DOWN,

34:43.067 --> 34:44.900
YOU KNOW IT CAN HAPPEN,

34:44.933 --> 34:46.667
BUT YOU NEVER THINK
IT'S GONNA HAPPEN.

34:46.699 --> 34:50.699
I HAVE NIGHTMARES ABOUT IT
ALL THE TIME

34:50.733 --> 34:52.600
THAT I CAN'T SAVE MY MEN.

34:55.132 --> 35:00.567
BUT THE THING ABOUT CRAB
FISHING, THOUGH, IS YOU --

35:00.600 --> 35:02.067
IT'S JUST LIKE WAR.

35:02.067 --> 35:05.700
YOU GOTTA PUT IT BEHIND YOU
AND JUST KEEP MOVING FORWARD.

35:09.667 --> 35:13.267
THAT'S A RISK WE TAKE...

35:13.300 --> 35:15.200
WORKING OUT AT SEA.

35:22.667 --> 35:25.267
Narrator:
ON THE NORTHWESTERN...

35:25.300 --> 35:27.800
Sig: I JUST NEED
TO GET OUT OF HERE.

35:32.333 --> 35:34.433
EDGAR AND NICK, COME UP.

35:34.467 --> 35:36.633
WE GOTTA MAKE A DECISION HERE.

35:36.667 --> 35:40.067
Narrator: ...SHAKEN BY THE LOSS
OF THE DESTINATION,

35:40.100 --> 35:44.767
CAPTAIN SIG HANSEN QUESTIONS HIS
ABILITY TO FINISH THE SEASON.

35:44.800 --> 35:45.933
I'M FREAKED OUT.

35:45.967 --> 35:50.067
I JUST LOST ONE
OF MY BEST FRIENDS.

35:50.100 --> 35:52.300
PROBABLY GONNA GET OUT OF HERE.

35:52.333 --> 35:56.300
I THINK -- I THINK I'VE --
I'VE DONE AS MUCH AS I CAN DO.

35:59.267 --> 36:02.800
YOU KNOW, I'M --
I'M STRESSING OUT MORE.

36:02.833 --> 36:04.167
I MEAN, AFTER HEARING THIS NEWS,

36:04.200 --> 36:06.667
I JUST WANT TO GET OUT OF HERE
AS FAST AS POSSIBLE.

36:09.767 --> 36:11.633
Narrator: SIG CALLS IT QUITS

36:11.667 --> 36:15.300
AND TURNS THE BOAT
TOWARDS ST. PAUL HARBOR.

36:15.333 --> 36:19.133
Sig: WE'LL OFFLOAD,
AND EDGAR WILL TAKE IT.

36:19.167 --> 36:20.467
YEAH.

36:20.500 --> 36:24.133
Narrator: ONCE AT DOCK, EDGAR
WILL GET BEHIND THE HELM.

36:24.167 --> 36:27.433
JUST BE SAFE.
OKAY?

36:30.633 --> 36:33.833
Sig: THEY'LL BE ALL RIGHT.
THEY KNOW WHAT THEY'RE DOING.

36:33.867 --> 36:42.233
*

36:42.267 --> 36:48.067
Narrator: 355 MILES SOUTHEAST
IN DUTCH HARBOR...

36:48.100 --> 36:50.067
Man:
WE'RE LISTING PRETTY HARD,

36:50.067 --> 36:56.367
BUT DOCK'S ONLY 500 YARDS
AWAY...LUCKILY.

36:56.400 --> 36:57.867
Narrator: ...THE WIZARD
ARRIVES AT DOCK

36:57.900 --> 37:01.433
AFTER TRAVELING 300 MILES
WITH A TEMPORARY FIX.

37:01.467 --> 37:04.067
I'VE STILL GOT A LITTLE BIT
OF THE LEANING TOWER GOING,

37:04.067 --> 37:05.167
BUT YOU KNOW WHAT?

37:05.200 --> 37:07.267
WE WILL ADDRESS THIS ISSUE,
PATCH THE HOLE

37:07.300 --> 37:09.400
BEFORE THIS BOAT SETS SAIL
FOR SEATTLE,

37:09.433 --> 37:10.733
I CAN GUARANTEE YOU THAT.

37:10.767 --> 37:14.200
Narrator: NOW, WITH CREW
AND VESSEL SAFELY IN PORT,

37:14.233 --> 37:18.333
CAPTAIN KEITH COLBURN CLOSES THE
BOOKS ON HIS 35th CRAB SEASON.

37:18.367 --> 37:20.433
Keith: ANOTHER ONE'S BEHIND US,
AND YOU KNOW WHAT?

37:20.467 --> 37:21.833
WE'RE REALLY FORTUNATE
RIGHT NOW.

37:21.867 --> 37:23.467
WE GOT LUCKY.

37:23.500 --> 37:25.433
I'M REALLY HAPPY
TO BE AT THE DOCK.

37:27.200 --> 37:28.367
GOD.

37:28.400 --> 37:33.867
*

37:33.900 --> 37:36.233
[ WIND HOWLING ]

37:36.267 --> 37:37.467
Narrator: ON THE SAGA...

37:37.500 --> 37:40.700
THE RIDE IN WAS NOT FUN.

37:40.733 --> 37:44.533
DESTINATION GOING DOWN
AND EVERYTHING ELSE.

37:44.567 --> 37:45.567
SPOOKY, MAN.

37:45.600 --> 37:46.967
I WAS SPOOKED LAST NIGHT.

37:47.067 --> 37:48.333
I STAYED UP HERE THE WHOLE TIME.

37:48.367 --> 37:51.933
THEN OLE TOOK IT THE LAST
FOUR HOURS AND LET ME SLEEP.

37:51.967 --> 37:53.533
Narrator:
LIKE THE REST OF THE FLEET,

37:53.567 --> 37:56.300
THE SINKING OF THE DESTINATION
LEFT ITS MARK

37:56.333 --> 37:58.833
ON CAPTAIN JAKE ANDERSON
AND HIS CREW.

37:58.867 --> 38:03.400
WE'RE GONNA GET THIS CRAB
OFF THE BOAT,

38:03.433 --> 38:06.667
GO BACK OUT, GO BACK TO FISHING.

38:06.700 --> 38:09.467
I CALLED THE WIFE,
AND SHE SAID, "COME HOME."

38:09.500 --> 38:11.767
SHE'S NOT HAPPY WITH ME
BEING UP HERE.

38:11.800 --> 38:15.533
ONCE SHE HEARD ABOUT THAT
OTHER BOAT, THE DESTINATION,

38:15.567 --> 38:16.900
THEN SHE JUST KIND OF THOUGHT,

38:16.933 --> 38:19.867
WELL, HEY, THERE'S NO NEED
FOR ME TO BE OUT HERE.

38:22.800 --> 38:24.767
I THINK THAT'S IT FOR ME.

38:24.800 --> 38:27.067
'CAUSE WHAT HAPPENED
ON DESTINATION

38:27.100 --> 38:29.533
CAN HAPPEN TO ANYBODY.

38:29.567 --> 38:35.800
SO, I'D RATHER BE HOME
THAN...BE SOMEWHERE ELSE, SO...

38:35.833 --> 38:37.867
NORMALLY, I DON'T
REALLY LIKE TO TAKE OFF

38:37.900 --> 38:39.767
IN THE MIDDLE OF THE SEASON.

38:53.300 --> 38:56.667
Narrator: WITH 51,000 POUNDS
STILL TO CATCH...

38:56.700 --> 38:58.833
WHAT NOW?

38:58.867 --> 39:00.467
EVERYBODY [BLEEP] LEAVING,
WHAT NOW?

39:00.500 --> 39:02.767
I DON'T KNOW.

39:02.800 --> 39:06.300
Narrator: ...JAKE IS BACK
TO A THREE-MAN DECK.

39:06.333 --> 39:11.533
NO MATTER HOW TORMENTING
THE SEAS MAY BE,

39:11.567 --> 39:13.867
YOU FINISH THE JOB.

39:13.900 --> 39:15.067
SEE YOU.

39:15.067 --> 39:16.133
-CANDITO.
-TAKE CARE, MAN.

39:16.167 --> 39:18.067
-ALL RIGHT, MAN.
-BE SAFE OUT THERE.

39:26.700 --> 39:29.400
Jake: I'M THIS CLOSE
TO FINISHING THE SEASON.

39:29.433 --> 39:32.333
I HAVE A GOAL, AND I'M
DETERMINED TO MEET THAT GOAL.

39:32.367 --> 39:34.633
[ "BEFORE THE FALLS"
BY EMILIA GLASER PLAYING ]

39:34.667 --> 39:41.067
*

39:41.067 --> 39:43.733
* TURNING AROUND

39:43.767 --> 39:45.667
* THROUGH EVERY THOUGHT

39:45.700 --> 39:49.933
* AND EVERY MEMORY
IN YOUR HEAD *

39:49.967 --> 39:55.300
* SEEING EVERYONE
AND EVERYWHERE YOU'VE BEEN *

39:55.333 --> 40:02.767
* YOU WONDER
WHERE IT ALL WENT BAD *

40:03.933 --> 40:12.233
* WONDERING WHERE IT
ALL WENT BLACK *

40:13.867 --> 40:17.100
Sig: RIGHT NOW,
I NEED TO GET OFF THE BOAT.

40:17.133 --> 40:20.400
YOU KNOW, I'VE -- I'M SPOOKED.

40:20.433 --> 40:23.133
I'M HEARTBROKEN.

40:23.167 --> 40:25.400
MY WIFE ASKED ME TO COME HOME.

40:25.433 --> 40:26.767
I WANT TO GO.

40:29.233 --> 40:36.200
* LET THIS MOMENT
BE SET FREE *

40:36.233 --> 40:39.900
* RUNNING FROM DARKNESS

40:39.933 --> 40:42.933
* YOU'VE GROWN TIRED

40:50.200 --> 40:51.300
YEAH.

40:55.267 --> 40:56.867
Pilot: I FEEL LIKE THAT WHOLE
FISHING COMMUNITY,

40:56.900 --> 41:00.167
WHEN SOMETHING HAPPENS,
THEY ALL KIND OF COME TOGETHER.

41:00.200 --> 41:03.233
YEAH.

41:03.267 --> 41:11.600
* YOU JUST WANT IT TO FLY,
FLY, FLY AWAY *

41:11.633 --> 41:16.067
* OOH, OOH, OOH

41:16.067 --> 41:20.167
* OOH, OOH, OOH

41:20.200 --> 41:24.067
* OOH, OOH, OOH

41:24.067 --> 41:28.067
* NOW, YOU'VE FLOWN AWAY

